<br>
&quot;Prohibition will work great injury to the cause of temperance. It is a species of intemperance within itself, for it goes beyond the bounds of reason in that it attempts to control a man's appetite by legislation and makes a crime out of things that are not crimes. A prohibition law strikes a blow at the very principles upon which our government was founded&quot; By Abraham Lincoln. We are resolved that U.S. federal government should legalize all drugs. Before I begin I'd like to provide the following information. I am not a druggie, nor will I ever be one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Arguement #1 - Drugs prohibition results in more drug deaths than if they were legal</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
A)         According to &quot;The Liberator On-line&quot; Vol. 7, No. 1, January 2002, &quot;Approximetly 7,000 people die each year from drug overdose....However, 80 percent of drug deaths (5,600) are due to impurities and other factors that would not be present in legal preparations.&quot; In addition to this, the legalization of drugs would allow users to regulate their dosages, and require suppliers to provide reliable information labels identifying dosages so users can monitor their intake and avoid fatal drug overdoses.  <br>
        <br>
B)         That benefit, of course, is obviously outweighed by the harms if the current amount of drug users drastically increases (over 5 times). Evidence suggests though, that the contrary is in fact the truth. The Volstead act (the prohibition of alcohol) in 1919 resulted in the increase of alcohol consumption. From what statistics show is that prohibition actually increased the use of alcohol after an initial drop in a time where alcohol consumption was actually at a decline. The &quot;getting away with something&quot; mentality obviously increased consumption, and it is likely that drug use is similar to prohibition in this aspect. Holland and Canada also disproves the myth. Holland has had drugs legal for over 30 years now, and a 1995 Dutch government published a report show that their consumption rate is has been falling from 1984  in addition their drug consumption rate is far better to ours, at less then half of our consumption rate.  &quot;In Canada, marijuana was banned in 1923. At the time, the weed was so little used in this country that anyone could have smoked a joint on the steps of most police stations. Despite anti-marijuana hysteria and an unforgiving attitude among law enforcers in those years, there were only 25 marijuana convictions up to 1946.In 1962, when an even tougher marijuana law was passed, the drug was still little known. But immediately after the law passed -- in the same year, in fact -- marijuana use began to grow exponentially.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Arguement #2 - Drug prohibition is indirectly the cause of a vast number of deaths.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
<br>
A)         Sharing of needles is partially responsible for the spreading of STD's. IV drug injection is responsible for 28% of HIV and AIDS cases according to a 1999 Center for Disease Control statistic. The sale of needles are currently illegal under prohibition laws, if sales were legal this problem would only be a fraction of what it is today.<br>
        <br>
B)         &quot;Many experts estimate that 50 percent of all crime directly or indirectly relates to robbing, maiming, and stealing to support a prohibitively expensive drug habit....Addicts are forced to commit crimes to pay for a habit that would be easily affordable if it were legal. Police sources have estimated that as much as half the property crime in some major cities is committed by drug users&quot; - Testimony of David Boaz, Executive Vice president of the Cato Institute, before the subcommittee on Crimanal Justice, Drug Policy, and Human Resources Committee on Government Reform; June 16, 1999 .  The murder rate is 8.22 per 100,000 in the U.S., the Dutch homicide rate is 1.8 per 100,000, less than one fourth the U.S. rate. In addition when prohibition was enacted there was a 54% rise in murder rates, after it was repealed the numbers declined rapidly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Arguement #3 - The drug war is economically stupid</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>
        <br>
A)         The current war on drugs is not working. Currently we spend $10 billion annually on combating drugs, &quot;After more than a decade of deepening drug war, U.S. surveys show that illicit drug use by American youth has increased almost every year since 1991. The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration admits that hard drugs are just as available, less expensive, and more pure than ever...U.S. drug policy has indeed been getting &quot;tougher.&quot; The administration's budget has increased from $1 billion in 1980 to $17 billion in 1998. The number of drug offenders imprisoned in the U.S. has increased 800% since 1980&quot;.  Our money is being wasted rather than programs just being underfunded . Combating drugs is providing no benefit, as the United State's drug consumption rate has been falling the same amount as Holland (40%). On DARE (Drug Abuse Resistance Education program) &quot;Since 1987, studies -- most funded by law enforcement agencies involved in the program -- have been conducted at 20 North Carolina schools; 31 Kentucky schools; 11 South Carolina schools; 36 Illinois schools; and 11 Canadian schools. The results were similar. The 1991 Kentucky study, the National Institute on Drug Abuse reported, found &quot;no statistically significant differences between experimental groups and control groups in the percentage of new users of ... cigarettes, smokeless tobacco, alcohol, marijuana.&quot;&quot; <br>
        <br>
B)          There are estimates of the worldwide drug trade as being high as approximetly $1 trillion dollars a year, with the United States being the largest consumer. Marijuana is one of California's largest exports, and Kentucky's biggest cash crop. If they were legal it would provide jobs for the economy , the government would be able to tax the drugs, and use that money to provide treatment for drug addicts, rather than the status quo with jails, which just act as a revolving door. <br>
        <br>
C)         War on terror is supported by drug prohibition. Those annoying T.V. commercials that the government aired futily to get people to stop using drugs actually had some truth to them. Afganistan is one of the world's largest heroin producers, selling $7 to $8 billion billion of drugs in the West a Year. The cost of drugs, as previously stated, would be a fraction of that if they were legal. Fight terrorism - legalize drugs.<br>
        <br>
D)         One out of every three people in jail are there because of non-violent crimes involving using or selling drugs . All these people are guilty of is using a drug that harmed themselves, no one else. One in every three people on paroll are violent crime offenders. Drug offenders take up violent crime commiters jail slots, forcing us to build more jails. I would much rather have the convicted rapist in jail than the guy that decided to smoke a joint. Maybe my moral code is screwed up though, you decide.<br>
